 The Industrial Tribunal, deciding a company and its workmen held that the ,company was not bona fide and that the should have been applied by the company in retrenching twelve of its workmen. In appeal to this Court, 
HELD: (i) Once the Tribunal finds that an employer has closed his ,factory as a matter of fact it is not concerned to go into the question as to the motive which guided him and to come to a conclusion that because of the previous history of the dispute between the employer and the employees the closure was not justified Such a closure cannot give rise to an industrial dispute. [135 D] Pipraich Sugar Mills Ltd. v. P.S.M. Mazdoor Union, [1957] 1 L.L.J. 235, K. M. Padmanabha Ayyar v. State of Madras, [1954] 1 L.L.J. 469, Tea Districts Labour Association, Calcutta v. Ex-employees of Tea Districts Labour Association and Anr. [1960] INSC 40; [1960] 3 S.C.R. 207, Hatisingh Manufacturing Co.
 Ltd. v. Union of India, [1960] S.C.R. 528, Express Newspapers (P) Ltd. v. The Workers, [1962] INSC 224; A.I.R. 1963 S.C. 569 and Andhra Prabha V. Madras Union of Journalists, [1967] INSC 144; [1967] 3 S.C.R. 901, applied.
 (ii) The plea as to the 'application of the principle 'last come first go' was not taken in the written statement of the Union and the Tribunal was not competent to go into that question at all. [135 F] 
